# portkill — engineering and rule guidelines

## Source of truth

- Product behavior and architecture: [PRD.md](PRD.md). If code and PRD disagree, update the PRD first, then the code.

## Stack and layout

- **Stack:** TypeScript, Node.js ≥ 18, `commander`, `tsup`, `vitest`, ESLint + Prettier.
- **Paths:** `src/index.ts` (CLI entry), `src/commands/kill.ts`, `src/core/finder.ts`, `src/core/killer.ts`, `src/utils/output.ts`, `src/utils/platform.ts`. Optional GUI: PRD §5.5 / `src/gui/`.
- **Platforms:** macOS and Linux only; no Windows. Port→PID logic lives in `platform.ts`; macOS uses `lsof`, Linux `fuser` or `/proc/net/tcp`.

## CLI contract (PRD §5)

- **Lines:** success `✔ Port <p> → killed (name, PID …)`; empty `ℹ Port <p> → no process found`; permission `✖ Port <p> → permission denied (try with sudo)`.
- **Exit codes:** `0` done; `1` general error; `2` no process on any port; `3` permission denied.
- **Flags:** `--force` / `-f`, `--dry-run` / `-n`, `--signal` / `-s` (default SIGTERM), `--verbose` / `-v`, `--version`, `--help` / `-h`.

## Code style

- Keep `core/` testable and isolate shell/`child_process` at clear boundaries.
- No drive-by refactors, unrelated files, or features not in the PRD.

## Adding new `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` files

- YAML frontmatter: required `description`; either `globs` **or** `alwaysApply: true`.
- One topic per file, keep it short (~50 lines when possible); include concrete examples.
- Prefer a specific name (e.g. `portkill-tests.mdc`) instead of copying this file wholesale.
